Your sort is still incorrect.  To see this, add the movies in a different order. 
Here is one possible algorithm, based on this article on [Insertion Sort][1]

```java
   public void insertSort() {
	  int in, out;

	  for (out = 1; out &lt; nElems; out++) {
		 in = out;
		 while (in &gt; 0 &amp;&amp; arrMovie[in - 1].Movie.compareToIgnoreCase(
		       arrMovie[in].Movie) &gt;= 0) {
			Movie temp = arrMovie[in];
			arrMovie[in] = arrMovie[in - 1];
			arrMovie[in - 1] = temp;
			--in;
		 }
	  }
    }
```

As you will see in the article, other algorithms offer some performance improvement.

  [1]: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Insertion_sort

**Solution**

    public void insertSort() {
        int in, out;

        for (out = 1; out &lt; nElems; out++) {

            Movie temp = arrMovie[out];
            in = out;
            //got rid of this ---&gt;   int j = in - 1;
            while (in &gt; 1 &amp;&amp; arrMovie[in - 1].Movie.compareToIgnoreCase(temp.Movie) &gt;= 0) {
                arrMovie[in] = arrMovie[in - 1];
                --in;
            }
            arrMovie[in] = temp;

        }

    }

**Reasoning**

In order for Insertion sort to work, you must compare the `arrMovie[out]` value to all of the values before it, until it gets to a value that is smaller than itself. In your scenario `j` remained constant, so you were comparing the same two movies repeatedly. If you need a good visual on insertion sort, visit https://visualgo.net/bn/sorting. 

You were just making the same comparison rather than continuing moving to the left and checking the other smaller values, and it was preventing your code from finishing properly.

